        ],
        [
          "Higher Education",
          "Blended Learning",
          "Collaborative Filtering",
          "University courses to take next",
          "1061 Psychology students",
          "47 course at a Canadian University ",
          "Course and Instructor Scores, Student Preferences",
          "Qualifier tags are built from the evaluations of a course using an ontology. \n\nWhen a course has not been taught before (and has no evaluations), essencially the algorithm provides it with an “unknown” constant ranking. \n\n",
          "Model recalibrated using cross-validation and variable weighting of AHP criteria (course difficulty, GPA, popularity, interest)",
          "– De-identification of student-level data\n\n– Aggregation of preferences by GPA group and course type– Normalization of grades [0–1]\n\n– Pairwise comparisons for AHP matrix consistency check",
          "Prediction of most likely course enrolments by student (ranking)",
          "{Accuracy: 0.64, RMSE: 0.072, Pearson r: 0.69}}",
          "– AHP effectively integrates identifiable + non-identifiable data to respect privacy constraints.\n\n– GPA and course difficulty are dominant predictors of course selection.\n\n– Model matches accuracy of prior identifiable-data approaches.\n\n– Emphasizes self-efficacy as a psychological factor in academic decision-making.",
          "– Limited generalizability (single program dataset).\n\n– AHP assumes stable weighting preferences across cohorts.\n\n– Manual feature scaling and expert-defined hierarchy.\n\n– Lacks behavioural, temporal, or motivational data.\n\n– Not a “true” recommender—predicts enrollment likelihood, not utility."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 10
    }
